Author-Name:    Shavell, Steven
Title:   Specific versus General Enforcement of Law. 
Journal: Journal of Political Economy
Pages: 1088-1108
Issue: 5
Volume: 99
Year: 1991
Month:  October 
Abstract:
  Optimal enforcement of law is examined in a model with specific
 enforcement effort--effort devoted toward apprehending individuals who
 have committed a single type of harmful act--and general enforcement
 effort--effort devoted toward apprehending individuals who have committed
 any of a range of harmful acts (a police officer on patrol, for instance,
 is able to apprehend many types of violators of law). If enforcement
 effort is specific, optimal sanctions are extreme for all acts. If
 enforcement effort is general, however, optimal sanctions rise with the
 harmfulness of acts and reach the extreme only for the most harmful acts.  Copyright 1991 by University of Chicago Press.
